<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911104-0088</DOCNO><DOCID>911104-0088.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Mesa L.P.:   Net Loss in Third Quarter   Widened to $35.8 Million</HL><DATE>11/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13</SO><CO>   MLP</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)OIL-SECONDARY (OIS)PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Mesa L.P., battered by falling natural-gas prices and theloss of revenue from properties sold earlier this year,posted a sharply wider net loss of $35.8 million, or 21 centsa unit, for the third quarter.   A year earlier, the Dallas-based oil and gas explorationand production company led by T. Boone Pickens Jr., had a netloss of $4.2 million, or 22 cents a unit, after securitiesgains of $32.4 million.</LP><TEXT>   Natural-gas production declined during the quarter to240.9 million cubic feet a day from 336.7 million cubic feeta year ago, primarily because of the sale earlier this yearof 17% of Mesa's oil and natural-gas reserves.   The company also cited &quot;the continued decline indeliverability&quot; from Gulf Coast properties and a decrease inproduction from its Hugoton field reserves &quot;due to fieldcompressor maintenance.&quot;   Meanwhile, natural gas prices have continued to soften,falling to $1.15 per 1,000 cubic feet during the quarter,from $1.34 a year earlier, contributing to a drop in revenueto $43.1 million from $65.9 million.</TEXT></DOC>